      <hedline>
        <hl1>Social Security: For All, Not the Few</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ben Myers letter predicts Pres Bush's plan would leave Social Security 'gutted, drawn and quartered,' and hanging in Crawford breeze</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We have heard George W. Bush's rhetoric many times before, starting with his moderate-sounding 2000 campaign. We have seen the stark contrast between the rhetoric of ''No Child Left Behind'' and the unfinanced educational mandates placed on the states.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We have heard George W. Bush's rhetoric many times before, starting with his moderate-sounding 2000 campaign. We have seen the stark contrast between the rhetoric of ''No Child Left Behind'' and the unfinanced educational mandates placed on the states.</p>
        <p>What reason is there to believe President Bush's latest pronouncements on Social Security this time rather than expecting the more likely possibility of a gutted, drawn and quartered Social Security left hanging in the Crawford breeze?</p>
        <p>With Mr. Bush, it's more of the same old, same old, a sort of Robin Hood in reverse.</p>
        <p>Ben Myers  Harvard, Mass., April 30, 2005</p>
      </block>
